To sort a single-linked list in descending order with a time complexity of O(n log n), we can use the Merge Sort algorithm. Here's an algorithmic description of the process:

1. If the list is empty or contains only one element, it is already sorted. Return the list.
2. Divide the list into two halves. This can be done by using the fast and slow pointer technique.
3. Recursively sort the two halves obtained in the previous step.
4. Merge the two sorted halves to create a single sorted list. This can be done by iterating through both halves and comparing the values at each node.
5. Return the merged sorted list.

Here is the algorithm in pseudocode:

function mergeSort(head):
    if head is null or head.next is null:
        return head

    // Splitting the list into two halves
    slow = head
    fast = head
    prev = null

    while fast is not null and fast.next is not null:
        fast = fast.next.next
        prev = slow
        slow = slow.next

    prev.next = null

    // Recursively sorting the two halves
    left = mergeSort(head)
    right = mergeSort(slow)

    // Merging the two sorted halves
    return merge(left, right)

function merge(left, right):
    if left is null:
        return right
    if right is null:
        return left

    if left.value >= right.value:
        merged = left
        merged.next = merge(left.next, right)
    else:
        merged = right
        merged.next = merge(left, right.next)

    return merged

To use this algorithm, simply call the mergeSort function passing the head of the linked list as an argument. The function will return the head of the sorted list in descending order.

