Here's a PHP script that generates a random password with exactly 15 characters, including a combination of uppercase and lowercase letters, numbers, and special characters. It also ensures that the generated password includes exactly two uppercase letters, three lowercase letters, four numbers, and six special characters.

```php
<?php
function generatePassword() {
    $uppercaseLetters = 'ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ';
    $lowercaseLetters = 'abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz';
    $numbers = '0123456789';
    $specialCharacters = '!@#$%^&*()-_+=<>?';

    $password = '';

    // Generate two uppercase letters
    for ($i = 0; $i < 2; $i++) {
        $password .= $uppercaseLetters[rand(0, strlen($uppercaseLetters) - 1)];
    }

    // Generate three lowercase letters
    for ($i = 0; $i < 3; $i++) {
        $password .= $lowercaseLetters[rand(0, strlen($lowercaseLetters) - 1)];
    }

    // Generate four numbers
    for ($i = 0; $i < 4; $i++) {
        $password .= $numbers[rand(0, strlen($numbers) - 1)];
    }

    // Generate six special characters
    for ($i = 0; $i < 6; $i++) {
        $password .= $specialCharacters[rand(0, strlen($specialCharacters) - 1)];
    }

    // Shuffle the password
    $password = str_shuffle($password);

    // Check if the password length is greater than 15 characters
    if (strlen($password) > 15) {
        $password = substr($password, 0, 15);
    }

    return $password;
}

$randomPassword = generatePassword();
echo $randomPassword;
?>
```

This script defines a `generatePassword()` function that generates a random password by randomly selecting characters from the defined character sets. It then ensures that the generated password contains exactly two uppercase letters, three lowercase letters, four numbers, and six special characters. Finally, the password is shuffled and truncated to exactly 15 characters if it exceeds that length.

