Here's a Java program that finds the first non-repeated character in a given string, ignoring any whitespace characters:

```java
public class FirstNonRepeatedCharacter {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String input = "hello 123&@^# world";
        char result = findFirstNonRepeatedCharacter(input);
        System.out.println("First non-repeated character: " + result);
    }

    public static char findFirstNonRepeatedCharacter(String str) {
        // Remove whitespace characters from the string
        String stringWithoutWhitespace = str.replaceAll("\\s+", "");

        // Create an array to keep track of character frequencies
        int[] frequencies = new int[256]; // Assuming ASCII characters

        // Count the frequency of each character in the string
        for (int i = 0; i < stringWithoutWhitespace.length(); i++) {
            char c = stringWithoutWhitespace.charAt(i);
            frequencies[c]++;
        }

        // Find the first non-repeated character
        for (int i = 0; i < stringWithoutWhitespace.length(); i++) {
            char c = stringWithoutWhitespace.charAt(i);
            if (frequencies[c] == 1) {
                return c;
            }
        }

        // If no non-repeated character found, return a default character
        return '\0';
    }
}
```

This program first removes all whitespace characters from the input string using the `replaceAll` method. Then, it creates an array to store the frequency of each character in the modified string.

After counting the frequencies, the program iterates through the modified string and checks if each character has a frequency of 1. The first character with a frequency of 1 is returned as the first non-repeated character.

