Here's a C++ algorithm that finds the longest common substring between two strings while handling strings containing both uppercase and lowercase letters:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>

std::string findLongestCommonSubstring(const std::string& str1, const std::string& str2) {
    int len1 = str1.length();
    int len2 = str2.length();
    int maxLength = 0;
    int endIndex = 0;

    // Create a 2D matrix to store the lengths of common substrings
    int dp[len1 + 1][len2 + 1] = {0};

    for (int i = 1; i <= len1; i++) {
        for (int j = 1; j <= len2; j++) {
            if (str1[i - 1] == str2[j - 1]) {
                dp[i][j] = dp[i - 1][j - 1] + 1;

                // Update the maxLength and endIndex if a longer substring is found
                if (dp[i][j] > maxLength) {
                    maxLength = dp[i][j];
                    endIndex = i - 1;
                }
            }
        }
    }

    // Extract the longest common substring from str1
    std::string longestSubstring = str1.substr(endIndex - maxLength + 1, maxLength);
    return longestSubstring;
}

int main() {
    std::string str1, str2;
    std::cout << "Enter the first string: ";
    std::getline(std::cin, str1);
    std::cout << "Enter the second string: ";
    std::getline(std::cin, str2);

    std::string longestCommonSubstring = findLongestCommonSubstring(str1, str2);
    std::cout << "Longest common substring: " << longestCommonSubstring << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

The algorithm uses dynamic programming and a 2D matrix to store the lengths of common substrings. It iterates over each character of both strings and updates the matrix based on the current character's equality. The algorithm keeps track of the maxLength and endIndex, allowing it to extract the longest common substring from str1 at the end. The time complexity of this algorithm is O(n^2), where n is the length of the longer string.

