Here is a function in Java to check if a string is a palindrome without using any built-in functions or libraries to reverse the string or remove spaces, punctuation, and capitalization:

```java
public class PalindromeChecker {
    public static boolean isPalindrome(String input) {
        // Convert the input string to lowercase
        String lowercaseInput = input.toLowerCase();

        // Create two pointers, one starting from the beginning and the other from the end of the string
        int start = 0;
        int end = lowercaseInput.length() - 1;

        while (start < end) {
            // Skip over non-alphanumeric characters from the start pointer
            while (start < end && !isAlphanumeric(lowercaseInput.charAt(start))) {
                start++;
            }

            // Skip over non-alphanumeric characters from the end pointer
            while (start < end && !isAlphanumeric(lowercaseInput.charAt(end))) {
                end--;
            }

            // If the alphanumeric characters at the start and end pointers are not equal, return false
            if (lowercaseInput.charAt(start) != lowercaseInput.charAt(end)) {
                return false;
            }

            // Move the pointers towards the center
            start++;
            end--;
        }

        // All alphanumeric characters have been checked and found to be equal, so the string is a palindrome
        return true;
    }

    // Helper method to check if a character is alphanumeric
    private static boolean isAlphanumeric(char c) {
        return (c >= 'a' && c <= 'z') || (c >= '0' && c <= '9');
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String input1 = "A man, a plan, a canal, Panama";
        String input2 = "Palindrome";

        System.out.println(isPalindrome(input1)); // Output: true
        System.out.println(isPalindrome(input2)); // Output: false
    }
}
```

The `isPalindrome` function uses two pointers to compare characters from the start and end of the input string. It skips over non-alphanumeric characters and compares the alphanumeric characters at the corresponding positions. If any characters are found to be different, it immediately returns false. If all alphanumeric characters are found to be equal, it returns true.

