```java
import java.util.Arrays;

public class Stack<T> {
    private int top;
    private T[] stackArray;
    private final int maxSize;

    public Stack() {
        this.top = -1;
        this.maxSize = 100;
        this.stackArray = (T[]) new Object[maxSize];
    }

    public void push(T element) {
        if (element == null) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Null elements are not allowed.");
        }
        if (top == maxSize - 1) {
            throw new IllegalStateException("Stack overflow.");
        }
        stackArray[++top] = element;
    }

    public T pop() {
        if (top == -1) {
            throw new IllegalStateException("Stack underflow.");
        }
        T element = stackArray[top];
        stackArray[top--] = null;
        return element;
    }

    public int size() {
        return top + 1;
    }

    public T peek() {
        if (top == -1) {
            throw new IllegalStateException("Stack is empty.");
        }
        return stackArray[top];
    }

    public void reverse() {
        int start = 0;
        int end = top;
        while (start < end) {
            T temp = stackArray[start];
            stackArray[start] = stackArray[end];
            stackArray[end] = temp;
            start++;
            end--;
        }
    }

    public void sort() {
        for (int i = 0; i < top; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j < top - i; j++) {
                if (((Comparable) stackArray[j]).compareTo(stackArray[j + 1]) > 0) {
                    T temp = stackArray[j];
                    stackArray[j] = stackArray[j + 1];
                    stackArray[j + 1] = temp;
                }
            }
        }
    }

    @Override
    public String toString() {
        return "Stack{" +
                "top=" + top +
                ", stackArray=" + Arrays.toString(stackArray) +
                '}';
    }
}
```

Explanation:
- The `Stack` class is designed as a generic class, allowing elements of any type to be stored in the stack.
- The class uses an array `stackArray` to store the elements of the stack.
- The `top` variable keeps track of the index of the top element in the stack.
- The maximum size of the stack is defined as `maxSize`.
- The `push` method checks if the stack is already full (`top == maxSize - 1`) and throws an `IllegalStateException` if it is. It also checks if the element to be pushed is `null` and throws an `IllegalArgumentException` if it is. Otherwise, it adds the element to the top of the stack.
- The `pop` method checks if the stack is empty (`top == -1`) and throws an `IllegalStateException` if it is. Otherwise, it removes and returns the top element of the stack.
- The `size` method returns the current size of the stack (`top + 1`).
- The `peek` method checks if the stack is empty and throws an `IllegalStateException` if it is. Otherwise, it returns the top element of the stack without removing it.
- The `reverse` method reverses the elements of the stack by swapping the elements from the start and end positions.
- The `sort` method sorts the elements in the stack in non-decreasing order using the bubble sort algorithm.
- The `toString` method is overridden to provide a string representation of the stack, including the current `top` index and the elements in the `stackArray`.

Note: In the `sort` method, a cast to `(Comparable)` is used to compare the elements. This assumes that all elements in the stack implement the `Comparable` interface. If this is not the case, a `ClassCastException` may occur at runtime.

