import java.util.Scanner;

public class StringRotation {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);

        // Step 1: Read the two strings from the user
        System.out.print("Enter the first string: ");
        String string1 = scanner.nextLine().replaceAll("\\s+", ""); // remove whitespace
        System.out.print("Enter the second string: ");
        String string2 = scanner.nextLine().replaceAll("\\s+", ""); // remove whitespace

        // Step 2: Check if the lengths of the two strings are equal
        if (string1.length() != string2.length()) {
            System.out.println("Not a rotation");
            return;
        }

        // Step 3: Create a temporary string
        String tempString = string1 + string1;

        // Step 4: Iterate through each character of the temporary string
        for (int i = 0; i < tempString.length(); i++) {
            char c = tempString.charAt(i);

            // Step 4a: Check if the character matches the first character of the second string
            if (c == string2.charAt(0)) {

                // Step 4b: Compare the subsequent characters of both strings
                boolean isRotation = true;
                for (int j = 1; j < string2.length(); j++) {
                    char c1 = tempString.charAt(i + j);
                    char c2 = string2.charAt(j);
                    if (c1 != c2) {
                        isRotation = false;
                        break;
                    }
                }

                // Step 4c: If all characters match, print "Rotation found"
                if (isRotation) {
                    System.out.println("Rotation found");
                    return;
                }
            }
        }

        // Step 5: No match found
        System.out.println("Not a rotation");
    }
}
```

This program first reads two strings from the user as input. It then checks if the lengths of the two strings are equal. If not, it prints "Not a rotation" and exits the program.

If the lengths are equal, it creates a temporary string by concatenating the first string with itself. It then iterates through each character of the temporary string. For each character, it checks if it matches the first character of the second string. If a match is found, it compares the subsequent characters of both strings. If all characters match, it prints "Rotation found" and exits the program.

If no match is found after iterating through all characters, it prints "Not a rotation". The program also handles cases where the strings contain duplicate characters and whitespace by removing the whitespace before performing the checks.

