Here's a Java program that performs a binary search on a sorted array of integers to find a given number. It returns the index of the first occurrence of the number if found, and -1 if not found. It also handles cases where the array is not sorted in ascending order and returns -1 in those cases.

```java
public class BinarySearch {
    public static int binarySearch(int[] arr, int target) {
        if (!isSorted(arr)) {
            return -1;
        }
        int left = 0;
        int right = arr.length - 1;

        while (left <= right) {
            int mid = left + (right - left) / 2;

            if (arr[mid] == target) {
                // Check if this is the first occurrence of the target
                while (mid > 0 && arr[mid - 1] == target) {
                    mid--;
                }
                return mid;
            }

            if (arr[mid] < target) {
                left = mid + 1;
            } else {
                right = mid - 1;
            }
        }

        return -1;
    }

    private static boolean isSorted(int[] arr) {
        for (int i = 1; i < arr.length; i++) {
            if (arr[i] < arr[i - 1]) {
                return false;
            }
        }
        return true;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] arr = {1, 2, 3, 3, 4, 5, 5, 5, 6};
        int target = 5;
        int index = binarySearch(arr, target);
        if (index != -1) {
            System.out.println("First occurrence of " + target + " found at index " + index);
        } else {
            System.out.println(target + " not found in the array or array is not sorted.");
        }
    }
}
```

This program first checks if the array is sorted using the `isSorted()` method. If it's not sorted, it returns -1. Otherwise, it performs the binary search by initializing the left and right pointers and repeatedly updating them based on the comparison between the target and the middle element of the array. If the target is found, it checks if it's the first occurrence by iterating backwards from the found index until the first element or until a different number is encountered.

