```javascript
function mergeAndSortDescending(arr1, arr2) {
  if (arr1.length !== arr2.length) {
    throw new Error('Input arrays must be of equal length');
  }

  const merged = [];
  let i = 0, j = 0;

  while (i < arr1.length && j < arr2.length) {
    if (arr1[i] > arr2[j]) {
      merged.push(arr1[i]);
      i++;
    } else if (arr1[i] < arr2[j]) {
      merged.push(arr2[j]);
      j++;
    } else {
      throw new Error('Input arrays must contain only unique elements');
    }
  }

  while (i < arr1.length) {
    merged.push(arr1[i]);
    i++;
  }

  while (j < arr2.length) {
    merged.push(arr2[j]);
    j++;
  }

  if (merged.length > 200) {
    throw new Error('Merged array exceeds maximum length of 200');
  }

  return merged;
}

// Example usage:
const arr1 = [9, 7, 5, 3, 1];
const arr2 = [8, 6, 4, 2, 0];

console.log(mergeAndSortDescending(arr1, arr2)); // Output: [9, 8, 7, 6, 5, 4, 3, 2, 1, 0]
```

This code takes two sorted arrays as input and merges them into a third array called `merged`. It checks if the input arrays are of equal length, throws an error if they are not, and then proceeds to merge the arrays.

The merging process is done by iterating over both arrays using two pointers (`i` and `j`) and comparing the elements at those positions. If the element in `arr1` is greater than the element in `arr2`, it is added to `merged` and `i` is incremented. If the element in `arr1` is less than the element in `arr2`, it is added to `merged` and `j` is incremented. If the elements are equal, it means there are duplicates and an error is thrown.

After the main merging loop, any remaining elements in `arr1` and `arr2` are added to `merged`. Finally, it checks if the length of `merged` exceeds the maximum length of 200 and throws an error if it does not.

Note that this code has a time complexity of O(n), where n is the length of the merged array, and a space complexity of O(1), as it only uses a fixed amount of memory regardless of the size of the input arrays.

