The time complexity of a self-balancing binary search tree, such as an AVL tree, is O(log n) for operations like insertion, deletion, and search. This is because the tree is rebalanced after each operation to ensure that the height of the tree remains logarithmic with respect to the number of elements.

Here is a piece of erroneous code that attempts to balance a binary search tree incorrectly:

```
void balanceBST(Node* root) {
    if (root == NULL) {
        return;
    }

    int balanceFactor = getHeight(root->left) - getHeight(root->right);

    if (balanceFactor > 1) {
        rotateRight(root);  // Incorrect rotation
    } else if (balanceFactor < -1) {
        rotateLeft(root);  // Incorrect rotation
    }

    balanceBST(root->left);
    balanceBST(root->right);
}
```

In this code, the `balanceBST` function attempts to balance the tree by checking the balance factor of each node and performing rotations if necessary. However, the rotations `rotateRight` and `rotateLeft` are incorrectly applied to the root node itself, instead of the appropriate subtree.

AVL tree rotation is a process used to balance the tree by rearranging the nodes while maintaining the binary search tree property. There are four types of rotations: left-rotate, right-rotate, left-right-rotate, and right-left-rotate. Each rotation is performed on a specific node or subtree to adjust the balance of the tree.

The impact of AVL tree rotation on the time complexity is crucial. When an operation, like insertion or deletion, causes the tree to become unbalanced, rotation is performed to restore the balance. This rotation process takes O(1) time since it only involves rearranging a few pointers.

By maintaining the balance of the tree through rotations, the worst-case height of the tree remains logarithmic. This ensures that operations like search, insertion, and deletion still have a time complexity of O(log n) even after the rotations. Without rotation, the tree could degenerate into a linked list, resulting in a worst-case time complexity of O(n).

