public static long leastCommonMultiple(int[] arr) {
    // Find the maximum absolute value of any integer in the array
    long maxNum = 0;
    for (int num : arr) {
        maxNum = Math.max(maxNum, Math.abs(num));
    }

    // Create an array to store the counts of prime factors
    int[] primeFactorCounts = new int[(int) (2 * Math.sqrt(maxNum) + 1)];

    // Iterate through each integer in the array
    for (int num : arr) {
        if (num == 0) {
            continue;
        }

        // Determine the prime factorization of the absolute value of the number
        int absNum = Math.abs(num);
        for (int i = 2; i * i <= absNum; i++) {
            int count = 0;
            while (absNum % i == 0) {
                count++;
                absNum /= i;
            }

            // Update the count of prime factors
            primeFactorCounts[i] = Math.max(primeFactorCounts[i], count);
        }

        if (absNum > 1) {
            primeFactorCounts[absNum] = Math.max(primeFactorCounts[absNum], 1);
        }
    }

    // Calculate the least common multiple
    long lcm = 1;
    for (int i = 2; i < primeFactorCounts.length; i++) {
        if (primeFactorCounts[i] > 0) {
            lcm *= Math.pow(i, primeFactorCounts[i]);
        }
    }

    // Handle negative least common multiple
    int negativeCount = 0;
    for (int num : arr) {
        if (num < 0) {
            negativeCount++;
        }
    }

    if (negativeCount % 2 != 0) {
        lcm *= -1;
    }

    return lcm;
}
```

Explanation:

1. We first find the maximum absolute value of any integer in the array by iterating through the array.
2. We create an array `primeFactorCounts` to store the counts of prime factors. The size of this array is determined by `2 * sqrt(maxNum) + 1`.
3. We iterate through each integer in the array.
4. For each integer, we find its prime factorization by repeatedly dividing it by prime numbers starting from 2. We update the count of prime factors in `primeFactorCounts`.
5. After finding the prime factorization of all integers, we calculate the least common multiple by multiplying the prime factors raised to their highest power.
6. We handle the case of negative least common multiple by counting the number of negative integers in the array. If the count is odd, we multiply the least common multiple by -1.
7. Finally, we return the least common multiple.

