Here is a recursive binary search algorithm to find the index of the first occurrence of the target number in a sorted array:

```java
public class Main {

    public static int findFirstOccurrence(int[] arr, int target) {
        return binarySearch(arr, target, 0, arr.length - 1);
    }

    private static int binarySearch(int[] arr, int target, int start, int end) {
        if (start > end) {
            return -1; // Target number not found
        }

        int mid = start + (end - start) / 2;

        if (arr[mid] == target && (mid == 0 || arr[mid - 1] != target)) {
            return mid; // Found the first occurrence of the target number
        } else if (arr[mid] >= target) {
            return binarySearch(arr, target, start, mid - 1); // Search in the left half
        } else {
            return binarySearch(arr, target, mid + 1, end); // Search in the right half
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] arr = {1, 2, 2, 2, 3, 4, 5};
        int target = 2;
        int firstOccurrence = findFirstOccurrence(arr, target);
        if (firstOccurrence != -1) {
            System.out.println("First occurrence of " + target + " is at index " + firstOccurrence);
        } else {
            System.out.println(target + " is not found in the array");
        }
    }
}
```

In this algorithm, we use the binary search approach to divide the array in half and recursively search for the target number. If the middle element is equal to the target number and is the first occurrence (i.e., the element before it is not equal to the target number), we return the index. If the middle element is greater than or equal to the target number, we recursively search in the left half of the array. Otherwise, we recursively search in the right half of the array.

The time complexity of this algorithm is O(log n) since we divide the array in half at each recursive step.

