Here's an example of a JavaScript function that checks if the first string contains the second string as a whole word:

```javascript
function containsWholeWord(str1, str2) {
  // Remove special characters and punctuation marks from the strings
  const regex = /[^a-zA-Z0-9]/g;
  const sanitizedStr1 = str1.replace(regex, ' ');
  const sanitizedStr2 = str2.replace(regex, ' ');

  // Create a regular expression with word boundaries around the second string
  const regex2 = new RegExp(`\\b${sanitizedStr2}\\b`);

  // Check if the first string contains the second string as a whole word
  return regex2.test(sanitizedStr1);
}

// Example usage:
console.log(containsWholeWord("Hello world! How are you?", "world")); // Output: true
console.log(containsWholeWord("The quick brown fox", "quick")); // Output: true
console.log(containsWholeWord("Hello, world!", "world")); // Output: false
console.log(containsWholeWord("Hello, world!", "World")); // Output: false (case-sensitive)
console.log(containsWholeWord("The quick brown fox", "quick brown")); // Output: false (not a whole word)
```

In this function, we first sanitize both input strings by removing any special characters and punctuation marks using a regular expression. Then, we create a regular expression with word boundaries (`\b`) around the second string. Finally, we use the `test` method of the regular expression to check if the first string contains the second string as a whole word. The function returns `true` if the second string is found as a whole word, and `false` otherwise.

