Here is a C# code that prints the first n terms of the series and ensures that each term is between 0 and 1000:

```csharp
using System;

class Program
{
    static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        Console.Write("Enter the number of terms (n): ");
        int n = int.Parse(Console.ReadLine());

        double previousTerm = 0;
        Random random = new Random();

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)
        {
            double randomNumber = random.NextDouble(); // Generates a random number between 0 and 1
            double currentTerm = previousTerm * Math.Sqrt(randomNumber);

            // Check if current term is within the range of 0 and 1000
            if (currentTerm < 0 || currentTerm > 1000)
            {
                Console.WriteLine($"Term {i + 1} is out of range.");
                break;
            }

            Console.WriteLine($"Term {i + 1}: {currentTerm}");
            previousTerm = currentTerm;
        }
    }
}
```

In this code, the user is prompted to enter the number of terms they want to print (n). The code then generates a random number between 0 and 1 for each term using the `NextDouble()` method of the `Random` class. The current term is obtained by multiplying the previous term by the square root of the random number.

The code checks if each term is within the desired range of 0 and 1000. If a term is outside this range, the loop is broken and a message is displayed indicating which term is out of range.

